ğŸ” What are Web Security Headers?
Web security headers are sent by the server along with HTTP responses.
They help protect against:
XSS attacks
Clickjacking
Content injection
Man-in-the-middle attacks

Examples include:
Content-Security-Policy (CSP)
X-Frame-Options
X-Content-Type-Options
Strict-Transport-Security (HSTS)
Referrer-Policy

ğŸ§­ Steps Performed
âœ” Step 1 â€” Open DVWA
Launched DVWA in the browser
Verified that the web application loads correctly

âœ” Step 2 â€” Open Developer Tools
Pressed F12 / Right-click â†’ Inspect
Opened Network tab

âœ” Step 3 â€” Check Response Headers
Reloaded DVWA page
Selected request from the Network list
Observed missing security headers such as:
Content-Security-Policy
X-Frame-Options
Strict-Transport-Security
This indicates the application is not following secure configuration practices.

âœ” Step 4 â€” Set DVWA Security Level
Navigated to DVWA Security page
Set security level to Low for testing

âœ” Step 5 â€” Open Brute Force Module
Went to Brute Force page in DVWA
Viewed the login form

âœ” Step 6 â€” Failed Login Attempt
Entered incorrect credentials
Login failed, showing invalid username/password

âœ” Step 7 â€” Successful Login Attempt
Used default weak credentials:
username: admin
password: password
Login was successful
Demonstrates how weak passwords enable brute-force attacks.

ğŸ§ª Results & Observations
DVWA is missing several important security headers
Application accepts weak credentials
Brute-force attack is possible
Security level Low exposes vulnerabilities deliberately

ğŸ” Security Recommendations
To secure a real-world web app:
Enforce strong password policies
Add account lockout or rate-limiting
Implement CAPTCHA on login pages
Use HTTPS with HSTS
Configure security headers:
X-Frame-Options
Content-Security-Policy
X-Content-Type-Options
Keep server and framework updated

âœ… Conclusion
Task 6 successfully demonstrated:
Security header analysis using browser dev tools
Brute-force vulnerability in DVWA
Impact of weak configuration and passwords
This exercise shows why secure headers and authentication policies are essential in web application security.

